If you need to be able to parse YAML 1.2, for which you would need my ruamel.yaml. you can actually hand in a `pathlib.Path` as well, and that will be correctly opened for you. 

Whereas the test for string/unicode is explicit in both PyYAML (for YAML 1.1) and ruamel.yaml (YAML 1.2 and 1.1) using `isinstance()`. The test for a `Path` is done differently, as the `pathlib` module is not available by default under Python 2 (although you can install  `pathlib2` and import `Path` from there). So if you were to do `isinstance(arg, Path)`, you would need to catch a possible exception.

Instead ruamel.yaml `load()` method, tests for the argument not having a `.read()` method, and having a `open` method, in which case it assumes the argument is a `Path`, opens it and calls itself:

    def load(self, stream):
        if not hasattr(stream, &#39;read&#39;) and hasattr(stream, &#39;open&#39;):
